A hidden gem. I had neither heard of this place nor read about it in articles of top Japanese restaurants, only saw its high rating in Google Maps. The place is small, with only a couple of tables and counters. Despite this, the menu is remarkably wide and the food is consistently excellent.

There is only one chef and one waitress. There might be a bit of a wait but it is worth it as the food is not just artfully presented but prepared with perfect technique.

The seasoning is on point; the chef is tasting and adjusting her flavour profiles. I rarely finish my miso soup but the one here is so full-bodied and satisfying, seemingly made from scratch (that is, by simmering kelp as opposed to rehydrating from powder), that I eagerly finished every last drop.

Final point: Price. You can still get lunch at the $10 price point here. Hallelujah!

text.text:
Overall, a very good restaurant!
I visited this restaurant six years ago when they first opened. I remember having the omurice at that time, and I loved it. Last night, we didn't order it. Instead, a range of other items.
The only reason I rated it short of five stars was because the portions could be increased slightly (in my opinion). Other than that, I still think that the food, service and atmosphere were excellent!
With service, they were slower to respond. It was a very busy night, especially having a jazz band play. Therefore, taking orders, refilling water, tending to customers, and providing the bill were slower. As we haven't visited regularly, I'm not sure if it's because of having live music (more patrons) but it was evident that there were only a few people on the floor. The handsome man at the bar also helped out with table service.
The atmosphere was as I remembered - simple but with character. It doesn't get much better than this. It feels homey and comfortable as a restaurant.
Food-wise, the Korean hot chicken was excellent! It wasn't very spicy, but that's subjective. We loved how the meat was smooth and juicy still.
The burger was also excellent! You can't compare it to something like 'Fat Burger' (entirely different styles and cuisines) but it was impressive. It certainly beats places like Earls, etc. in our views.
And the Pacific cod was amazing too! You can tell the quality is different.
In every dish, it was evident that the food was fresh and freshly made. No nonsense here!
We ended up with a bill just over $100 (not including tips). I think that's pretty reasonable, but, again, a slight increase to the portions would perfect it in our opinions.
Parking is available on the streets.
They accept all forms of payments.

text.text:
Ooooooohhh I did it again!! Another five star.  But first, to get here wasn’t five stars.   You know how they say “location location location”? Well, it doesn’t apply here. The location can be a bit sketchy and when they first opened up, I admittedly wasn’t a fan.  But my Japanese food critique friend and I decided to go since we were near a destination that was close by and decided to try Dosanko.  Ok cut to the chase right?
Yes BAM! Best Japanese Omlettes we’ve had in town outside of Japan.  BAM great quality ingredients and I love places that support local. BAM this place is really Japanese!!! Oh waitaminit the chef is classically trained and he’s not Japanese? No Way!  Yabaii!  Could that be their secret weapon ? I think the secret recipe is Aki and her secret agent is her chef and like we say in Japan, it’s all about the “service”.    Politeness served with  each dish of near perfection.  I wish I could come more often.  Dosanko deserves a bigger star. I hope you can support their dream.  There are not many truly owned and run Japanese places in town.  This happens to be one of the best examples of how a Japanese place should be.  Now if only they could serve at Japanese prices.  But that’s a dream because Vancouvers city has taxed us out of affordability for small business.

I'd had my eye on Dosanko for quite awhile and we finally got to try it out! This isn't your run of the mill Japanese restaurant. There's no sushi to be found on their menu. They are described as a Japanese Homestyle Yoshoku Restaurant. Yoshoku is a term which refers to Western food, so Dosanko serves up Japanse dishes with Western influence.

Mugi Cha
Grape Calpico Soda
Kinpira
Crispy Cheesy Onigiri
Farm Vegetable Tempura
Beef Belly Katsu Sandwich
Omu Rice
Pacific Cod Fish Katsu

We'd had a Cheese Yaki Onigiri in Seattle earlier this year, and until now I didn't know of any places within Vancouver that served it. Even Takenaka's Onigiri Cafe, which is Vancouver's one and only dedicated Onigiri restaurant, does not have a Cheese Onigiri on their menu. Dosanko not only impressed us by having Cheesy Onigiri on their menu, but they also managed to cook it better than the one we had in Seattle!

We'd been happy already with the one in Seattle, but that was because it was the first and only Cheese Onigiri we'd ever had. There was no basis of comparison. After trying this one from Dosanko, there's no way we'd go back to the one in Seattle. Upon a first glance, Dosanko's Cheesy Onigiri was paler in colour and didn't look as attractive as the one we had in Seattle. Biting into it was a different story though. It was way less greasy than the one in Seattle, and so it felt better in our stomachs.

"O mu goodness," the Omu Rice was soooo good! They gave us plenty of tomato sauce for the Omu Rice too, so we were able to pour some of the extra tomato sauce onto the plain rice that came with one of the other dishes.

Every other dish was executed to perfection as well. This was such a wonderful meal and we will definitely be back sometime to try out their lunch special!

Five stars for the foods; however, it was a hot summer's day and there was no air conditioning in the restaurant, so....4 stars overall when factoring in the ambiance.

Service: Good
Parking: Paid parking on the street. Free parking a couple of blocks away.
Location: 566 Powell St.

I would still go back to try the other items on their menu.

The vibe brought me back to Japan as most or all the staff appears to be Japanese and the atmosphere just feels Japan!

We walked in around 1pm on a Friday, a few min to wait however definitely gets busy.

We ordered tan-tan ramen, press salmon sushi, blue fin and avocado carpaccio and my ebi mayo. Ramen was awesome - rich and creamy but not too heavy. Noodles al dente was perfect match. My 9 yo cleaned the bowl. Carpaccio was great, sometimes the avocado overpowering the rest of the ingredients as the tuna was so good. Pressed salmon was seared, had a Smokey aroma and flavor but thought it was overpowered by the rice and sauce. My ebi, I liked the least and wouldn’t order again. It wasn’t crispy, as expected of Japanese tempura, but soft, perhaps too much mayo.

Overall would recommend as there are plenty of dishes to try and had great service and ambience.

The cheese tofu is really more of a dessert than an appetizer in my opinion and is pretty interesting too if you wanted to try it out. The different iced fruit tea drinks are also excellent!

text.text: This place was so cool!! The decore was on point, the drinks, were wickedly delicious, and the food was perfection. The staff was awesome and so inviting and honestly it’s just a cool spot. It’s simple but perfectly balanced and executed. Really good spot for a fun and unique dining experience.
